[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Some things on the screen update in response to user input.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] For example, clicking an image gallery switches the active image.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] In React, data that changes over time is called *state.* You can add state to any component, and update it as needed.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] In this chapter, you’ll learn how to write components that handle interactions, update their state, and display different output over time.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] React lets you add *event handlers* to your JSX.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Event handlers are your own functions that will be triggered in response to user interactions like clicking, hovering, focusing on form inputs, and so on.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Built-in components like `<button>` only support built-in browser events like `onClick`.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] However, you can also create your own components, and give their event handler props any application-specific names that you like.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **Responding to Events** to learn how to add event handlers.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Components often need to change what’s on the screen as a result of an interaction.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Typing into the form should update the input field, clicking “next” on an image carousel should change which image is displayed, clicking “buy” puts a product in the shopping cart.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Components need to “remember” things: the current input value, the current image, the shopping cart.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] You can add state to a component with a `useState` Hook.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] *Hooks* are special functions that let your components use React features (state is one of those features).
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] The `useState` Hook lets you declare a state variable.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] It takes the initial state and returns a pair of values: the current state, and a state setter function that lets you update it.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **State: A Component’s Memory** to learn how to remember a value and update it on interaction.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Before your components are displayed on the screen, they must be rendered by React.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Understanding the steps in this process will help you think about how your code executes and explain its behavior.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Imagine that your components are cooks in the kitchen, assembling tasty dishes from ingredients.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] In this scenario, React is the waiter who puts in requests from customers and brings them their orders.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **Render and Commit** to learn the lifecycle of a UI update.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Unlike regular JavaScript variables, React state behaves more like a snapshot.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Setting it does not change the state variable you already have, but instead triggers a re-render.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] This behavior helps you avoid subtle bugs.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Try to guess what happens if you press “Send” first and *then* change the recipient to Bob.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Whose name will appear in the `alert` five seconds later?
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **State as a Snapshot** to learn why state appears “fixed” and unchanging inside the event handlers.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] This component is buggy: clicking “+3” increments the score only once.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] State as a Snapshot explains why this is happening.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Setting state requests a new re-render, but does not change it in the already running code.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] So `score` continues to be `0` right after you call `setScore(score + 1)`.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] You can fix this by passing an *updater function* when setting state.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Notice how replacing `setScore(score + 1)` with `setScore(s => s + 1)` fixes the “+3” button.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] This lets you queue multiple state updates.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **Queueing a Series of State Updates** to learn how to queue a sequence of state updates.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] State can hold any kind of JavaScript value, including objects.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] But you shouldn’t change objects and arrays that you hold in the React state directly.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Instead, when you want to update an object and array, you need to create a new one (or make a copy of an existing one), and then update the state to use that copy.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Usually, you will use the `...` spread syntax to copy objects and arrays that you want to change.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **Updating Objects in State** to learn how to update objects correctly.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Arrays are another type of mutable JavaScript objects you can store in state and should treat as read-only.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Read **Updating Arrays in State** to learn how to update arrays correctly.
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Head over to Responding to Events to start reading this chapter page by page!
[src:react-docs/adding-interactivity] Or, if you’re already familiar with these topics, why not read about Managing State?
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React is a JavaScript library for rendering user interfaces (UI).
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] UI is built from small units like buttons, text, and images.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React lets you combine them into reusable, nestable *components.* From web sites to phone apps, everything on the screen can be broken down into components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] In this chapter, you’ll learn to create, customize, and conditionally display React components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React applications are built from isolated pieces of UI called *components*.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] A React component is a JavaScript function that you can sprinkle with markup.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Components can be as small as a button, or as large as an entire page.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Your First Component** to learn how to declare and use React components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] You can declare many components in one file, but large files can get difficult to navigate.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Importing and Exporting Components** to learn how to split components into their own files.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Each React component is a JavaScript function that may contain some markup that React renders into the browser.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React components use a syntax extension called JSX to represent that markup.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] JSX looks a lot like HTML, but it is a bit stricter and can display dynamic information.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Writing Markup with JSX** to learn how to write valid JSX.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] JSX lets you write HTML-like markup inside a JavaScript file, keeping rendering logic and content in the same place.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Sometimes you will want to add a little JavaScript logic or reference a dynamic property inside that markup.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **JavaScript in JSX with Curly Braces** to learn how to access JavaScript data from JSX.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React components use *props* to communicate with each other.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Every parent component can pass some information to its child components by giving them props.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Props might remind you of HTML attributes, but you can pass any JavaScript value through them, including objects, arrays, functions, and even JSX!
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Passing Props to a Component** to learn how to pass and read props.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Your components will often need to display different things depending on different conditions.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] In React, you can conditionally render JSX using JavaScript syntax like `if` statements, `&&`, and `? :` operators.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Conditional Rendering** to learn the different ways to render content conditionally.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] You will often want to display multiple similar components from a collection of data.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] You can use JavaScript’s `filter()` and `map()` with React to filter and transform your array of data into an array of components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] For each array item, you will need to specify a `key`.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Usually, you will want to use an ID from the database as a `key`.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Keys let React keep track of each item’s place in the list even if the list changes.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Rendering Lists** to learn how to render a list of components, and how to choose a key.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] By strictly only writing your components as pure functions, you can avoid an entire class of baffling bugs and unpredictable behavior as your codebase grows.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Keeping Components Pure** to learn how to write components as pure, predictable functions.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] React uses trees to model the relationships between components and modules.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] A React render tree is a representation of the parent and child relationship between components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Components near the top of the tree, near the root component, are considered top-level components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Components with no child components are leaf components.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] This categorization of components is useful for understanding data flow and rendering performance.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Modelling the relationship between JavaScript modules is another useful way to understand your app.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] We refer to it as a module dependency tree.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] A dependency tree is often used by build tools to bundle all the relevant JavaScript code for the client to download and render.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] A large bundle size regresses user experience for React apps.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Understanding the module dependency tree is helpful to debug such issues.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Read **Your UI as a Tree** to learn how to create a render and module dependency trees for a React app and how they’re useful mental models for improving user experience and performance.
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Head over to Your First Component to start reading this chapter page by page!
[src:react-docs/describing-the-ui] Or, if you’re already familiar with these topics, why not read about Adding Interactivity?
[src:react-docs/learn] This page will give you an introduction to 80% of the React concepts that you will use on a daily basis.
[src:react-docs/learn] React apps are made out of *components*.
[src:react-docs/learn] A component is a piece of the UI (user interface) that has its own logic and appearance.
[src:react-docs/learn] A component can be as small as a button, or as large as an entire page.
[src:react-docs/learn] Notice that `<MyButton />` starts with a capital letter.
[src:react-docs/learn] That’s how you know it’s a React component.
[src:react-docs/learn] React component names must always start with a capital letter, while HTML tags must be lowercase.
[src:react-docs/learn] The `export default` keywords specify the main component in the file.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you’re not familiar with some piece of JavaScript syntax, MDN and javascript.info have great references.
[src:react-docs/learn] The markup syntax you’ve seen above is called *JSX*.
[src:react-docs/learn] It is optional, but most React projects use JSX for its convenience.
[src:react-docs/learn] All of the tools we recommend for local development support JSX out of the box.
[src:react-docs/learn] Your component also can’t return multiple JSX tags.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you have a lot of HTML to port to JSX, you can use an online converter.
[src:react-docs/learn] In React, you specify a CSS class with `className`.
[src:react-docs/learn] React does not prescribe how you add CSS files.
[src:react-docs/learn] In the simplest case, you’ll add a `<link>` tag to your HTML.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you use a build tool or a framework, consult its documentation to learn how to add a CSS file to your project.
[src:react-docs/learn] JSX lets you put markup into JavaScript.
[src:react-docs/learn] Curly braces let you “escape back” into JavaScript so that you can embed some variable from your code and display it to the user.
[src:react-docs/learn] You can also “escape into JavaScript” from JSX attributes, but you have to use curly braces *instead of* quotes.
[src:react-docs/learn] In the above example, `style={{}}` is not a special syntax, but a regular `{}` object inside the `style={ }` JSX curly braces.
[src:react-docs/learn] You can use the `style` attribute when your styles depend on JavaScript variables.
[src:react-docs/learn] In React, there is no special syntax for writing conditions.
[src:react-docs/learn] Instead, you’ll use the same techniques as you use when writing regular JavaScript code.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you prefer more compact code, you can use the conditional `?` operator.
[src:react-docs/learn] All of these approaches also work for conditionally specifying attributes.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you’re unfamiliar with some of this JavaScript syntax, you can start by always using `if...else`.
[src:react-docs/learn] You will rely on JavaScript features like `for` loop and the array `map()` function to render lists of components.
[src:react-docs/learn] Notice how `<li>` has a `key` attribute.
[src:react-docs/learn] For each item in a list, you should pass a string or a number that uniquely identifies that item among its siblings.
[src:react-docs/learn] Usually, a key should be coming from your data, such as a database ID.
[src:react-docs/learn] React uses your keys to know what happened if you later insert, delete, or reorder the items.
[src:react-docs/learn] Notice how `onClick={handleClick}` has no parentheses at the end!
[src:react-docs/learn] Do not *call* the event handler function: you only need to *pass it down*.
[src:react-docs/learn] React will call your event handler when the user clicks the button.
[src:react-docs/learn] Often, you’ll want your component to “remember” some information and display it.
[src:react-docs/learn] For example, maybe you want to count the number of times a button is clicked.
[src:react-docs/learn] To do this, add *state* to your component.
[src:react-docs/learn] You’ll get two things from `useState`: the current state (`count`), and the function that lets you update it (`setCount`).
[src:react-docs/learn] You can give them any names, but the convention is to write `[something, setSomething]`.
[src:react-docs/learn] The first time the button is displayed, `count` will be `0` because you passed `0` to `useState()`.
[src:react-docs/learn] When you want to change state, call `setCount()` and pass the new value to it.
[src:react-docs/learn] React will call your component function again.
[src:react-docs/learn] If you render the same component multiple times, each will get its own state.
[src:react-docs/learn] Notice how each button “remembers” its own `count` state and doesn’t affect other buttons.
[src:react-docs/learn] Functions starting with `use` are called *Hooks*.
[src:react-docs/learn] `useState` is a built-in Hook provided by React.
[src:react-docs/learn] You can find other built-in Hooks in the API reference.
[src:react-docs/learn] You can also write your own Hooks by combining the existing ones.
[src:react-docs/learn] Hooks are more restrictive than other functions.
[src:react-docs/learn] You can only call Hooks *at the top* of your components (or other Hooks).
[src:react-docs/learn] If you want to use `useState` in a condition or a loop, extract a new component and put it there.
[src:react-docs/learn] However, often you’ll need components to *share data and always update together*.
[src:react-docs/learn] To make both `MyButton` components display the same `count` and update together, you need to move the state from the individual buttons “upwards” to the closest component containing all of them.
[src:react-docs/learn] Now when you click either button, the `count` in `MyApp` will change, which will change both of the counts in `MyButton`.
[src:react-docs/learn] Here’s how you can express this in code.
[src:react-docs/learn] Then, *pass the state down* from `MyApp` to each `MyButton`, together with the shared click handler.
[src:react-docs/learn] The information you pass down like this is called *props*.
[src:react-docs/learn] Now the `MyApp` component contains the `count` state and the `handleClick` event handler, and *passes both of them down as props* to each of the buttons.
[src:react-docs/learn] When you click the button, the `onClick` handler fires.
[src:react-docs/learn] Each button’s `onClick` prop was set to the `handleClick` function inside `MyApp`, so the code inside of it runs.
[src:react-docs/learn] That code calls `setCount(count + 1)`, incrementing the `count` state variable.
[src:react-docs/learn] The new `count` value is passed as a prop to each button, so they all show the new value.
[src:react-docs/learn] By moving state up, you’ve shared it between components.
[src:react-docs/learn] By now, you know the basics of how to write React code!
[src:react-docs/learn] Check out the Tutorial to put them into practice and build your first mini-app with React.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] As your application grows, it helps to be more intentional about how your state is organized and how the data flows between your components.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Redundant or duplicate state is a common source of bugs.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] In this chapter, you’ll learn how to structure your state well, how to keep your state update logic maintainable, and how to share state between distant components.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] With React, you won’t modify the UI from code directly.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] For example, you won’t write commands like “disable the button”, “enable the button”, “show the success message”, etc.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Instead, you will describe the UI you want to see for the different visual states of your component (“initial state”, “typing state”, “success state”), and then trigger the state changes in response to user input.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] This is similar to how designers think about UI.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Note how it uses the `status` state variable to determine whether to enable or disable the submit button, and whether to show the success message instead.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Reacting to Input with State** to learn how to approach interactions with a state-driven mindset.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Structuring state well can make a difference between a component that is pleasant to modify and debug, and one that is a constant source of bugs.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] The most important principle is that state shouldn’t contain redundant or duplicated information.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] If there’s unnecessary state, it’s easy to forget to update it, and introduce bugs!
[src:react-docs/managing-state] This might seem like a small change, but many bugs in React apps are fixed this way.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Choosing the State Structure** to learn how to design the state shape to avoid bugs.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Sometimes, you want the state of two components to always change together.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] To do it, remove state from both of them, move it to their closest common parent, and then pass it down to them via props.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] This is known as “lifting state up”, and it’s one of the most common things you will do writing React code.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] In this example, only one panel should be active at a time.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] To achieve this, instead of keeping the active state inside each individual panel, the parent component holds the state and specifies the props for its children.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Sharing State Between Components** to learn how to lift state up and keep components in sync.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] When you re-render a component, React needs to decide which parts of the tree to keep (and update), and which parts to discard or re-create from scratch.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] In most cases, React’s automatic behavior works well enough.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] By default, React preserves the parts of the tree that “match up” with the previously rendered component tree.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] However, sometimes this is not what you want.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] In this chat app, typing a message and then switching the recipient does not reset the input.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] React lets you override the default behavior, and *force* a component to reset its state by passing it a different `key`, like `<Chat key={email} />`.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] This tells React that if the recipient is different, it should be considered a *different* `Chat` component that needs to be re-created from scratch with the new data (and UI like inputs).
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Now switching between the recipients resets the input field—even though you render the same component.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Preserving and Resetting State** to learn the lifetime of state and how to control it.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Components with many state updates spread across many event handlers can get overwhelming.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] For these cases, you can consolidate all the state update logic outside your component in a single function, called “reducer”.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Your event handlers become concise because they only specify the user “actions”.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] At the bottom of the file, the reducer function specifies how the state should update in response to each action!
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Extracting State Logic into a Reducer** to learn how to consolidate logic in the reducer function.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Usually, you will pass information from a parent component to a child component via props.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] But passing props can become inconvenient if you need to pass some prop through many components, or if many components need the same information.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Context lets the parent component make some information available to any component in the tree below it—no matter how deep it is—without passing it explicitly through props.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Here, the `Heading` component determines its heading level by “asking” the closest `Section` for its level.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Each `Section` tracks its own level by asking the parent `Section` and adding one to it.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Every `Section` provides information to all components below it without passing props—it does that through context.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Passing Data Deeply with Context** to learn about using context as an alternative to passing props.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Reducers let you consolidate a component’s state update logic.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Context lets you pass information deep down to other components.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] You can combine reducers and context together to manage state of a complex screen.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] With this approach, a parent component with complex state manages it with a reducer.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Other components anywhere deep in the tree can read its state via context.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] They can also dispatch actions to update that state.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Read **Scaling Up with Reducer and Context** to learn how state management scales in a growing app.
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Head over to Reacting to Input with State to start reading this chapter page by page!
[src:react-docs/managing-state] Or, if you’re already familiar with these topics, why not read about Escape Hatches?
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] `useEffect` is a React Hook that lets you synchronize a component with an external system.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Some components need to stay connected to the network, some browser API, or a third-party library, while they are displayed on the page.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] A list of dependencies including every value from your component used inside of those functions.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] When the `ChatRoom` component above gets added to the page, it will connect to the chat room with the initial `serverUrl` and `roomId`.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] An Effect lets you keep your component synchronized with some external system (like a chat service).
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] In this example, the `ChatRoom` component uses an Effect to stay connected to an external system defined in `chat.js`.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Press “Open chat” to make the `ChatRoom` component appear.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] This sandbox runs in development mode, so there is an extra connect-and-disconnect cycle, as explained here.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Try changing the `roomId` and `serverUrl` using the dropdown and the input, and see how the Effect re-connects to the chat.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Press “Close chat” to see the Effect disconnect one last time.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Effects are an “escape hatch”: you use them when you need to “step outside React” and when there is no better built-in solution for your use case.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] If you find yourself often needing to manually write Effects, it’s usually a sign that you need to extract some custom Hooks for common behaviors your components rely on.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] There are also many excellent custom Hooks for every purpose available in the React ecosystem.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Learn more about wrapping Effects in custom Hooks.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] This example is identical to one of the earlier examples, but the logic is extracted to a custom Hook.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Sometimes, you want to keep an external system synchronized to some prop or state of your component.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] For example, if you have a third-party map widget or a video player component written without React, you can use an Effect to call methods on it that make its state match the current state of your React component.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] This Effect creates an instance of a `MapWidget` class defined in `map-widget.js`.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] In this example, a cleanup function is not needed because the `MapWidget` class manages only the DOM node that was passed to it.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] After the `Map` React component is removed from the tree, both the DOM node and the `MapWidget` class instance will be automatically garbage-collected by the browser JavaScript engine.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] You can use an Effect to fetch data for your component.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Note that if you use a framework, using your framework’s data fetching mechanism will be a lot more efficient than writing Effects manually.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Note the `ignore` variable which is initialized to `false`, and is set to `true` during cleanup.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] This ensures your code doesn’t suffer from “race conditions”: network responses may arrive in a different order than you sent them.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Writing data fetching directly in Effects gets repetitive and makes it difficult to add optimizations like caching and server rendering later.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] It’s easier to use a custom Hook—either your own or maintained by the community.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Writing `fetch` calls inside Effects is a popular way to fetch data, especially in fully client-side apps.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] This list of downsides is not specific to React.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] It applies to fetching data on mount with any library.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] You can continue fetching data directly in Effects if neither of these approaches suit you.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] If either `serverUrl` or `roomId` change, your Effect will reconnect to the chat using the new values.
[src:react-docs/react-useeffect] Now that `serverUrl` is not a reactive value (and can’t change on a re-render), it doesn’t need to be a dependency.
